pr_review_body:
@samuelcolvin, please beware that this PR introduces breaking changes

This was previously a valid usecase, but with these changes it will raise an error:
```py
def test_custom_getter_dict():
    class TestCls:
        x = 1
        y = 2

    def custom_getter_dict(obj):
        assert isinstance(obj, TestCls)
        return {'x': 42, 'y': 24}
```

Thanks for addressing my previous comments and for adding all these tests! Overall changes look good. I left a few comments though, plus the following suggestions/questions.

What is the message the user gets after the last retry? Could you add a sample output of running a command that is rate limited?

Could you please update the PR description to make it clear how many retries we are making and what is the min/max time for each of them or until we give up retrying?

Now that I'm taking another look at the code, I think we can avoid all the duplicate `try-except(429)` code if we create a retry decorator for 429 exceptions only. Something like the following:
```
def retry_429(func):
    @retry("RateLimitException")
    def wrap():
        try:
            func()
        except:
            raise Exception("RateLimitException")
    return wrap

@retry_429
def list_status():
    raise Exception("429")
```
We can either add it on the existing `_with_retry` methods and move them in the DbfsService, or directly on the methods in `DbfsService`. I don't have a strong preference over one or the other. If we go with the first option, we can even make a single method per dbfs operation, with a `rateLimitRetry` boolean option based on which we do the retry or not (it can default to true).

@pulbitz 
> Only certain afreecatv streamer get this error.

Could you please check whether these changes are working for you, so that this can be merged and #3407 be closed?

@matthewdeng I've left some comments, PTAL

Overall this looks great, love the composition idea. We could expand it to `start_training` as well. 

It would be great if we could use the pytorch profiler directly instead of providing our own wrapper, though - do you think that'd be possible?

@bgpierc mostly docstring stuff as I am getting familiar with the new code.

I support adding the DEM functions to a new module `horizon.py`.  Perhaps more of the DEM functions could become private, unless you think that a user will need them to work with DEM files in their code.

I think the three public functions from JPalakapillyKWH's PR should go to `shading.py`.

Thanks very much for this! I left two suggestions for your consideration.

@StrikerRUS since we haven't been successful getting any other reviews with more OpenCL understanding to review...could you test the generated wheels one more time? There have been some additional commits since you last tested (https://github.com/microsoft/LightGBM/pull/5252#issuecomment-1159807098).

I'm also interested in understanding how much larger the package's wheels will be as a result of this change. Large wheels can introduce some new classes of problems for users (for example, those using function-as-a-service services that have fairly strict limits on disk usage, see https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas/issues/30741#issuecomment-752751976). I'll wait until another commit is pushed to check that (since the previous Azure DevOps build is gone now).
